{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515831"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:35:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:35:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12502"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12502"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.06,0.02,0.02,0.8]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5008"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77782"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5008"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12502"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63297"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4640"},{"type":"tags","id":"4748"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8299"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26720"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44380"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77782"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of a palmar rash. He is concerned that it does not seem to be self-resolving. The patient denies itch and tenderness in the affected area. He does not recall any prior exposure to new handwash or skincare products. At the same time as the palmar rash onset, he also reports experiencing some myalgias, headaches, and subjective fevers. He recalls noticing painless enlarged non-tender lymph nodes in the groin approximately three weeks prior, which has persisted. He has a history of hay fever and asthma that are both well controlled. On examination, he is afebrile. The palmar rash is shown (Image). There are no other lesions, rashes, or ulcers elsewhere.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the rash?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Coxsackievirus infection (Hand-foot-and-mouth disease)","Reactive arthritis (Reiter\u0027s syndrome)","Plantar wart (verruca plantaris)","Pityriasis rosea","Syphilis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s systemic symptoms of myalgia, headache, subjective fever, painless lymphadenopathy, and the characteristic palmar rash, this presentation is consistent with secondary\u003Cstrong\u003E syphilis\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESyphilis is caused by the bacterium \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E, a spirochete with a characteristic corkscrew shape. It is primarily transmitted through sexual contact, including vaginal, anal, and oral intercourse, but it can also be transmitted vertically from mother to fetus during pregnancy, resulting in congenital syphilis. In terms of disease progression, there is primary, secondary, and tertiary syphilis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn primary syphilis, patients typically present with a solitary, firm, painless ulcer known as a chancre, which develops at the site of inoculation, most commonly on the genital region (e.g., penile shaft, vagina, cervix, or anal area) or extragenital sites like the mouth or lips. The chancre is characterized by a well-defined margin, an indurated base, and is often accompanied by painless regional lymphadenopathy (e.g., inguinal nodes in genital cases). Chancres are usually painless, may go unnoticed (especially if internal), and heal spontaneously within 3\u20136 weeks, even without treatment, as the infection progresses to secondary syphilis. Primary syphilis is often asymptomatic apart from the chancre, but the presence of painless lymphadenopathy in the draining region is a common associated finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn secondary syphilis, patients typically present with a rash that begins on the trunk and spreads to involve the palms and soles, emerging 3\u20138 weeks after the primary stage. This is often accompanied by non-specific systemic symptoms such as fever, myalgia, and fatigue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn tertiary syphilis (20-30 years), patients clinically present with neurological and cutaneous involvement. In terms of treatment, treatment for primary and secondary syphilis (\u003C1 year) is in the form of a single IM dose of benzathine penicillin G while treatment for tertiary syphilis is in the form of weekly IM benzathine penicillin G injections for 3 weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoxsackievirus infection\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with vesicular lesions on the hands, feet, and in the mouth, along with fever and sore throat. While it can affect adults, it is more common in children and does not typically present with painless lymphadenopathy or the systemic symptoms described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReactive arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with a rash on the palms and soles (keratoderma blennorrhagica), but this is typically accompanied by arthritis and urethritis. The absence of joint symptoms or urethral discharge makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlantar warts (verruca plantaris)\u003C/strong\u003E are benign lesions most commonly caused by human papillomavirus. Plantar warts are often caused by HPV 1 and 2, and have a rough, keratinous surface and can be tender on application of lateral and direct pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPityriasis rosea\u003C/strong\u003E is most common in teenagers and young adults, and often presents on the chest, abdomen, or back instead of the palmoplantar regions. Classically, pityriasis rosea begins as a single slightly raised oval patch approximately 3-5 cm in diameter with peripheral scaling (herald patch) then later develops to form an eruption of smaller, scaly erythematous oval patches affecting the trunk in a \u0027Christmas tree\u0027 distribution. Pityriasis rosea is self-limiting in nature, and resolves in 2-3 months.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Palmoplantar rash in secondary syphilis is a key diagnostic feature.","Secondary syphilis can present with systemic symptoms such as myalgias, headaches, and fever.","Painless lymphadenopathy is a common finding in secondary syphilis."],"references":["Tan C, Zhu WY. Arthralgia and scaly rashes over the palms and the soles. Braz J Infect Dis. 2016 Sep-Oct;20(5):505-6. doi: 10.1016/j.bjid.2016.07.007. Epub 2016 Aug 16. PMID: 27542870; PMCID: PMC9425497. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27542870/","Tudor ME, Al Aboud AM, Leslie SW, et al. Syphilis. [Updated 2022 Nov 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534780/","Usatine RP. The palms and soles. West J Med. 2000 Sep;173(3):160-1. doi: 10.1136/ewjm.173.3.160. PMID: 10986171; PMCID: PMC1071050. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1071050/","Chambers LC, Srinivasan S, Lukehart SA, Ocbamichael N, Morgan JL, Lowens MS, Fredricks DN, Golden MR, Manhart LE. Primary Syphilis in the Male Urethra: A Case Report. Clin Infect Dis. 2019 Mar 19;68(7):1231-1234. doi: 10.1093/cid/ciy771. PMID: 30202933; PMCID: PMC6424071. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30202933/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63297"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12502"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19665"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19665"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8f84430e-a110-482b-a7c1-3988d8a334de.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8f84430e-a110-482b-a7c1-3988d8a334de.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":513,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63297"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T10:25:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T10:27:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5008"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77782"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51: